1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:05,560
 Hypertext Transfer Protocol is the protocol that browsers use to talk to servers.

2
00:00:05,560 --> 00:00:10,720
 Now we've used it for all kinds of other things because it turns out that it's a super simple

3
00:00:10,720 --> 00:00:12,920
 and super elegant protocol.

4
00:00:12,920 --> 00:00:15,060
 This goes to a long time ago.

5
00:00:15,060 --> 00:00:21,960
 This protocol was invented in 1990, which is like going on 30 years ago.

6
00:00:21,960 --> 00:00:26,520
 Yeah, going on 30 years ago now or more.

7
00:00:26,520 --> 00:00:28,160
 And there were many protocols.

8
00:00:28,160 --> 00:00:32,560
 You would have one piece of software, and there was server software and client software.

9
00:00:32,560 --> 00:00:36,760
 You had to match them up, and then you'd talk to the right port with this server software.

10
00:00:36,760 --> 00:00:42,520
 And one of the inventions of Tim Berners-Lee and Robert Caillou at CERN was that we came

11
00:00:42,520 --> 00:00:47,280
 up with this notion of instead of lots of pieces of software, we would have one piece

12
00:00:47,280 --> 00:00:52,260
 of software called the web browser, and it would be multi-protocol.

13
00:00:52,260 --> 00:00:56,200
 And so we have this thing called the URL, or Uniform Resource Locator, and we just sling

14
00:00:56,200 --> 00:00:57,200
 these around.

15
00:00:57,200 --> 00:00:58,520
 We couldn't use them.

16
00:00:58,520 --> 00:01:03,600
 But these things, this was itself an amazing innovation in 1990, because in the old days

17
00:01:03,600 --> 00:01:07,760
 it would be like, use this piece of software and talk to this address.

18
00:01:07,760 --> 00:01:12,800
 So the URL captured three really important, very separate things.

19
00:01:12,800 --> 00:01:16,160
 The first thing it did is it allowed for multiple protocols.

20
00:01:16,160 --> 00:01:22,000
 The one that you mostly have seen is HTTP or HTTPS, but that's a protocol, FTP colon

21
00:01:22,000 --> 00:01:25,120
 or mail to colon might be the other ones that you've seen.

22
00:01:25,120 --> 00:01:27,960
 And then a host and then a document.

23
00:01:27,960 --> 00:01:35,600
 And that host is a domain name, which is a nice symbolic way to get a server address.

24
00:01:35,600 --> 00:01:42,360
 And that eventually resolves to an IP address like 141.206.14.22 or something.

25
00:01:42,360 --> 00:01:47,840
 And then the document within that server, that /page1.htm, is the document in the server.

26
00:01:47,840 --> 00:01:53,480
 And I'm just saying, before 1990, there were many protocols and we did many things.

27
00:01:53,480 --> 00:02:01,160
 But after 1990, this one protocol, HTTP, found its way into so many awesome solutions that

28
00:02:01,160 --> 00:02:07,320
 it's by far, other than email, the dominant protocol that we use on the internet.

29
00:02:07,320 --> 00:02:12,080
 Like I said, it was invented at CERN by Tim Berners-Lee and Robert Caillou to retrieve documents and

30
00:02:12,080 --> 00:02:13,760
 images.

31
00:02:13,760 --> 00:02:17,600
 And as soon as they built it, because it was all the other protocols that came, most of

32
00:02:17,600 --> 00:02:22,200
 the other protocols, were kind of complex because we're computer scientists and we make

33
00:02:22,200 --> 00:02:24,440
 complex things and we love complex things.

34
00:02:24,440 --> 00:02:27,520
 And we're very, very good at complex things.

35
00:02:27,520 --> 00:02:34,560
 But this was, you know, when the web was being built, Tim and Robert were not like, we're

36
00:02:34,560 --> 00:02:36,520
 going to make the greatest thing ever.

37
00:02:36,520 --> 00:02:38,560
 We're just going to make a simple thing.

38
00:02:38,560 --> 00:02:43,160
 So they made a simple thing, but it turned out to be the greatest thing ever because

39
00:02:43,160 --> 00:02:47,780
 different engineers would be like, oh, wow, I can use that a little different way.

40
00:02:47,780 --> 00:02:50,120
 And the grounding of it was super simple.

41
00:02:50,120 --> 00:02:54,680
 And the basic concept was you connect to a server, you figure out where it is, you send

42
00:02:54,680 --> 00:03:00,500
 a single command with a bit of extra data, and then you get back something, a document.

43
00:03:00,500 --> 00:03:03,560
 It could be an image, it could be data, it could be HTML.

44
00:03:03,560 --> 00:03:07,040
 And it was really amazing, right?

45
00:03:07,040 --> 00:03:11,880
 And so the sockets, the underlying sockets are the things that make the phone call.

46
00:03:11,880 --> 00:03:17,800
 HTTP is what we do once this phone call has been established.

47
00:03:17,800 --> 00:03:22,320
 So one of the things that made the internet so successful starting in the 1960s was a

48
00:03:22,320 --> 00:03:29,240
 radical openness, a very, we're all around the same campfire feeling, very friendly,

49
00:03:29,240 --> 00:03:31,760
 respectful, that still allowed criticism.

50
00:03:31,760 --> 00:03:36,600
 There wasn't like one super genius that designed this or one company that designed this.

51
00:03:36,600 --> 00:03:38,400
 This was a collaboration.

52
00:03:38,400 --> 00:03:41,840
 And the collaboration was around a set of open standards and meetings to help build

53
00:03:41,840 --> 00:03:42,840
 these standards.

54
00:03:42,840 --> 00:03:47,120
 And they were called RFCs, they were called Request for Comments.

55
00:03:47,120 --> 00:03:51,880
 And there was a group that built these called the Internet Engineering Task Force, the IETF.

56
00:03:51,880 --> 00:03:55,760
 And the Request for Comments is a fun notion.

57
00:03:55,760 --> 00:04:02,920
 We're looking here at a September 1981 document, which is 40 years old about now.

58
00:04:02,920 --> 00:04:04,640
 And it's called a Request for Comments.

59
00:04:04,640 --> 00:04:11,000
 And the idea is as engineers, we might have a design that everyone thinks is the greatest

60
00:04:11,000 --> 00:04:14,720
 thing ever, but we should always question.

61
00:04:14,720 --> 00:04:16,000
 No design is perfect.

62
00:04:16,000 --> 00:04:18,440
 No design is beyond question.

63
00:04:18,440 --> 00:04:21,120
 No design is beyond commentary.

64
00:04:21,120 --> 00:04:28,560
 And so even when they're 40 years old and used worldwide and dang amazing, we still

65
00:04:28,560 --> 00:04:30,660
 say there is room for improvement.

66
00:04:30,660 --> 00:04:36,800
 And so this talks about, I think this one is IP, and there's an IPv6.

67
00:04:36,800 --> 00:04:41,480
 There's another one if you look for this RFC that we're looking at here, there'd be IPv6.

68
00:04:41,480 --> 00:04:42,480
 And you'd start reading it.

69
00:04:42,480 --> 00:04:46,720
 I mean, it's pretty dense reading, but as an engineer, it gives you all the details

70
00:04:46,720 --> 00:04:50,320
 to build a router or build a piece of software or build whatever.

71
00:04:50,320 --> 00:04:54,160
 And these are 100% public documents.

72
00:04:54,160 --> 00:04:58,400
 And the idea was that no company, because literally the companies that were around in

73
00:04:58,400 --> 00:05:05,320
 1960, if they had said Burroughs or Sperry owns the internet or digital equipment owns

74
00:05:05,320 --> 00:05:10,040
 the internet, they're all out of business because they didn't make good choices, but

75
00:05:10,040 --> 00:05:14,920
 the market was able to make good choices and because the commons were these open standards

76
00:05:14,920 --> 00:05:19,800
 and open specifications, new companies like Sun Microsystems and new operating systems

77
00:05:19,800 --> 00:05:25,400
 like Linux could come in and even Windows could come in and participate as full participants

78
00:05:25,400 --> 00:05:29,160
 because they just read these specs and all of a sudden they're interoperating with everybody

79
00:05:29,160 --> 00:05:30,160
 else.

80
00:05:30,160 --> 00:05:34,000
 This is fundamental and foundational to how the internet works.

81
00:05:34,000 --> 00:05:38,540
 And I'm not saying you're supposed to go read them, but it's just fascinating to understand

82
00:05:38,540 --> 00:05:45,640
 that the entire technological infrastructure upon which the internet is built is free,

83
00:05:45,640 --> 00:05:52,920
 license free, royalty free, and you could build a brand new gadget and you could hook

84
00:05:52,920 --> 00:05:55,520
 it to the internet by reading the specifications.

85
00:05:55,520 --> 00:05:58,160
 You don't have to pay a developer's license or nothing.

86
00:05:58,160 --> 00:05:59,960
 It's dang, it's cool.

87
00:05:59,960 --> 00:06:02,960
 Sorry, I'm just a little bit too excited about that.

88
00:06:02,960 --> 00:06:06,200
 So let's take a look at one of these in particular.

89
00:06:06,200 --> 00:06:10,840
 Now this is probably supplanted, but we'll look at RFC 2616.

90
00:06:10,840 --> 00:06:12,320
 They go up in numbers.

91
00:06:12,320 --> 00:06:20,000
 And so this is HTTP, hypertext transfer protocol.

92
00:06:20,000 --> 00:06:25,000
 And if you wanted to build a web browser or a web server, you could read this document.

93
00:06:25,000 --> 00:06:27,360
 Go ahead, read the document.

94
00:06:27,360 --> 00:06:32,520
 And if you read down far enough, you'll say, oh, this is how you make a request, blah,

95
00:06:32,520 --> 00:06:33,520
 blah, blah.

96
00:06:33,520 --> 00:06:37,680
 It's got a header and it's got like a carriage return line feed and then a message body.

97
00:06:37,680 --> 00:06:38,680
 And you got to do this.

98
00:06:38,680 --> 00:06:40,760
 And this is what it looks like.

99
00:06:40,760 --> 00:06:41,760
 This is how it works.

100
00:06:41,760 --> 00:06:42,760
 Right?

101
00:06:42,760 --> 00:06:46,440
 And so at some point you're deep in this document and you're finding out in this page right

102
00:06:46,440 --> 00:06:51,340
 here of this document how your browser is supposed to format it.

103
00:06:51,340 --> 00:06:56,280
 And this tells both the client and the server what the rules of the protocol are.

104
00:06:56,280 --> 00:07:00,440
 Now it's a lot easier to just for me to tell you.

105
00:07:00,440 --> 00:07:06,320
 So you connect to the server on a socket, usually port 80 or port 443.

106
00:07:06,320 --> 00:07:14,180
 And then the client is supposed to make the first sound-- it makes the first request.

107
00:07:14,180 --> 00:07:19,040
 It sends a line with a carriage return line feed at the end that has the characters--

108
00:07:19,040 --> 00:07:24,760
 there are other ones-- but get get space, a URL space, and then a protocol.

109
00:07:24,760 --> 00:07:28,760
 And right now I'm using this HTTP 1.0 because I can do it by hand.

110
00:07:28,760 --> 00:07:29,760
 Right?

111
00:07:29,760 --> 00:07:32,160
 And so you ask for a document.

112
00:07:32,160 --> 00:07:37,560
 And then you can optionally send some header information, things like what language this

113
00:07:37,560 --> 00:07:43,820
 browser-- person that this browser prefers, what are the capabilities of this browser,

114
00:07:43,820 --> 00:07:44,920
 what version browser we have.

115
00:07:44,920 --> 00:07:45,920
 So there's a series of things.

116
00:07:45,920 --> 00:07:49,080
 You say, give me this document and here's something about the browser that's requesting

117
00:07:49,080 --> 00:07:53,120
 the document, including information like cookies that are being said.

118
00:07:53,120 --> 00:07:58,240
 So in case you want to know who is doing this request because you've logged somebody in

119
00:07:58,240 --> 00:08:02,760
 and set a cookie to indicate that they're logged in, that's all sent on this GET request.

120
00:08:02,760 --> 00:08:04,760
 But we'll not send the headers.

121
00:08:04,760 --> 00:08:07,720
 There's actually incoming headers and then outgoing headers.

122
00:08:07,720 --> 00:08:13,640
 We'll see these when we start looking at Firefox's debugging console.

123
00:08:13,640 --> 00:08:18,720
 And so this is an entire interaction that you can do on your laptop.

124
00:08:18,720 --> 00:08:24,080
 Now I'm not going to do it for you, but I would note that the program Telnet that this

125
00:08:24,080 --> 00:08:27,200
 uses has been removed from most computers.

126
00:08:27,200 --> 00:08:28,520
 It makes me sad.

127
00:08:28,520 --> 00:08:32,160
 They think of it as a security hole because it doesn't use encrypted connections.

128
00:08:32,160 --> 00:08:36,320
 Like port 80 is not an encrypted connection.

129
00:08:36,320 --> 00:08:42,680
 But ultimately, you can install-- go search on your favorite search engine and find out

130
00:08:42,680 --> 00:08:44,320
 how to install Telnet.

131
00:08:44,320 --> 00:08:49,000
 But if you get in a command line, whether it's a Windows command line or a Mac command line

132
00:08:49,000 --> 00:08:54,320
 or a Linux command line, and you get Telnet properly installed, you can type the following

133
00:08:54,320 --> 00:09:00,920
 command, telnet datapr4e.org 80, and then hit Enter.

134
00:09:00,920 --> 00:09:05,360
 And at that point-- so Telnet originally was used to log into computers.

135
00:09:05,360 --> 00:09:09,120
 But if the server we're talking to and the protocol that we're talking to is simple enough--

136
00:09:09,120 --> 00:09:14,360
 and in this case, HTTP/1 is simple enough for us to be able to do this-- we're actually

137
00:09:14,360 --> 00:09:15,720
 talking to the server.

138
00:09:15,720 --> 00:09:20,000
 Because remember I said that these are applications.

139
00:09:20,000 --> 00:09:21,740
 Your browser is not talking to files.

140
00:09:21,740 --> 00:09:25,200
 Your browser is talking to an application on a server, and the server might give you

141
00:09:25,200 --> 00:09:26,440
 back a file.

142
00:09:26,440 --> 00:09:28,160
 So it's really talking to a piece of software.

143
00:09:28,160 --> 00:09:32,040
 And we'll see this in more detail in the next section.

144
00:09:32,040 --> 00:09:38,800
 And so what will happen is because the HTTP protocol requires that the client speak first,

145
00:09:38,800 --> 00:09:39,800
 we have to type.

146
00:09:39,800 --> 00:09:44,640
 Now, if you can get this working and type wrong things-- and type a couple of enters,

147
00:09:44,640 --> 00:09:48,340
 new lines-- you will see that you're talking to a piece of software.

148
00:09:48,340 --> 00:09:51,400
 And it will say, you have violated my protocol.

149
00:09:51,400 --> 00:09:55,400
 You're not talking to a thing that has any online help or user interface or anything

150
00:09:55,400 --> 00:09:56,440
 like that.

151
00:09:56,440 --> 00:10:00,880
 You're talking to a server, and your job is to request some data using the proper format

152
00:10:00,880 --> 00:10:06,000
 because you read the specifications about the proper format, right?

153
00:10:06,000 --> 00:10:09,200
 So in this particular one, we just-- it's easier to cut and paste this because some

154
00:10:09,200 --> 00:10:13,200
 of these servers, if you don't type fast enough, they'll be like, you're not of software.

155
00:10:13,200 --> 00:10:14,200
 You're a human.

156
00:10:14,200 --> 00:10:15,200
 Quit playing with me.

157
00:10:15,200 --> 00:10:19,540
 Like, you talk to Facebook or something, and you can talk to Facebook and see what happens

158
00:10:19,540 --> 00:10:22,120
 on port 80.

159
00:10:22,120 --> 00:10:23,720
 And it will time you out really fast.

160
00:10:23,720 --> 00:10:25,920
 So it's good to have a cut and paste buffer.

161
00:10:25,920 --> 00:10:28,160
 So you paste this get command in.

162
00:10:28,160 --> 00:10:32,120
 And the other thing that's important is you got to put an extra blank line.

163
00:10:32,120 --> 00:10:35,920
 And this extra blank line is to indicate that you're not going to send any of those headers

164
00:10:35,920 --> 00:10:42,400
 if we were going to send things like what language we would prefer or what formats we

165
00:10:42,400 --> 00:10:45,580
 would prefer as a browser.

166
00:10:45,580 --> 00:10:50,280
 The browser has certain languages and other configurations and login information.

167
00:10:50,280 --> 00:10:55,480
 And that can get sent up to the web server along with the request for the document.

168
00:10:55,480 --> 00:10:57,240
 And we would be able to type them in here.

169
00:10:57,240 --> 00:10:59,520
 But we're not going to do that in this very simple.

170
00:10:59,520 --> 00:11:02,760
 We're just going to say enter, which means no more headers.

171
00:11:02,760 --> 00:11:05,600
 If you were putting in headers, you'd type header, header, header, header, and then enter

172
00:11:05,600 --> 00:11:06,920
 on a blank line.

173
00:11:06,920 --> 00:11:09,720
 And then the server would know that our request was finished.

174
00:11:09,720 --> 00:11:12,600
 But we can just ask for a page.

175
00:11:12,600 --> 00:11:16,880
 And then what the server does is it sends us back two pieces of information.

176
00:11:16,880 --> 00:11:18,560
 First it sends us headers.

177
00:11:18,560 --> 00:11:22,120
 The first header is HTTP 1.1 200 OK.

178
00:11:22,120 --> 00:11:23,660
 That's actually a status line.

179
00:11:23,660 --> 00:11:26,640
 Now you'd have to go read the documentation on what that works.

180
00:11:26,640 --> 00:11:29,880
 But for example, 200 means that you got a document.

181
00:11:29,880 --> 00:11:31,400
 Another one that you might have seen is 404.

182
00:11:31,400 --> 00:11:33,800
 It might say 404 not found.

183
00:11:33,800 --> 00:11:37,720
 So if you go to a web page and it doesn't exist, something will say 404 in your browser

184
00:11:37,720 --> 00:11:41,640
 usually unless it says here's a search box, go find it.

185
00:11:41,640 --> 00:11:43,840
 But there's a status.

186
00:11:43,840 --> 00:11:49,840
 And so the thing that you're typing, page1.htm, may or may not be on this server.

187
00:11:49,840 --> 00:11:53,360
 If it is, then you'll get a 200 OK and the data.

188
00:11:53,360 --> 00:11:55,600
 Or you'll get a 404 not found.

189
00:11:55,600 --> 00:11:59,000
 And then we get some response data, some header response.

190
00:11:59,000 --> 00:12:02,680
 And this header response looks pretty much like the same format of the data we would

191
00:12:02,680 --> 00:12:08,160
 have sent into the browser if we were sending things like that in there.

192
00:12:08,160 --> 00:12:13,000
 It's what the data is, what the server we're using, last modified.

193
00:12:13,000 --> 00:12:18,440
 And one of the important things is what kind of content are you about to see.

194
00:12:18,440 --> 00:12:22,680
 Content type, in this case, is text/html, which means the thing coming next.

195
00:12:22,680 --> 00:12:27,280
 And then there's a blank line, and the blank line is our indication as we're reading this

196
00:12:27,280 --> 00:12:32,800
 data that we have finished the header, which is really metadata about the page we're retrieving,

197
00:12:32,800 --> 00:12:34,400
 and the actual page itself.

198
00:12:34,400 --> 00:12:37,960
 And so the rest of this page is the actual data.

199
00:12:37,960 --> 00:12:42,560
 And we know the format of it because we were told before the page starts.

200
00:12:42,560 --> 00:12:48,800
 This could be image/png, this could be xml, application/xml, and it could be JSON.

201
00:12:48,800 --> 00:12:50,560
 It could be like anything.

202
00:12:50,560 --> 00:12:54,120
 And then the browser is supposed to-- and if this was an image, it would be like garble,

203
00:12:54,120 --> 00:12:56,440
 garble, garble, garble, garble, garble, garble, right?

204
00:12:56,440 --> 00:12:59,760
 It would be all garbled stuff that we can't really see.

205
00:12:59,760 --> 00:13:04,920
 But the browser knows what a png or jpeg looks like, and it shows it to you.

206
00:13:04,920 --> 00:13:09,720
 And it basically uses this text/html to tell you what's going on.

207
00:13:09,720 --> 00:13:13,000
 And so this, then, your browser has read all this information.

208
00:13:13,000 --> 00:13:18,080
 It has both the metadata and the data about the retrieved page, and then its job is to

209
00:13:18,080 --> 00:13:24,180
 sort of produce a pretty rendered version of the page and show it to you.

210
00:13:24,180 --> 00:13:26,520
 And that is the request recycle.

211
00:13:26,520 --> 00:13:28,540
 Again, you don't have to do this.

212
00:13:28,540 --> 00:13:30,620
 You can just sort of believe that it's done here.

213
00:13:30,620 --> 00:13:34,680
 But if you want to install Telnet on your system, it's not a bad thing to install Telnet.

214
00:13:34,680 --> 00:13:37,120
 It's kind of a classic, fun thing.

215
00:13:37,120 --> 00:13:40,520
 It's far less useful than it was in the early days, because we used to use Telnet to test

216
00:13:40,520 --> 00:13:41,520
 everything.

217
00:13:41,520 --> 00:13:46,520
 Now we've got browser developer consoles that are way easier than Telnet.

218
00:13:46,520 --> 00:13:49,000
 But it's kind of a cool thing.

219
00:13:49,000 --> 00:13:54,360
 Feel free to do this, and you'll be like, I know what's really going on.

220
00:13:54,360 --> 00:14:03,320
 And so I'm a big fan of using the console, of using the terminal, of using text-based

221
00:14:03,320 --> 00:14:04,320
 interfaces.

222
00:14:04,320 --> 00:14:06,440
 They're actually way more accessible.

223
00:14:06,440 --> 00:14:08,560
 I think it's awesome.

224
00:14:08,560 --> 00:14:16,340
 And in a way, all these fancy graphical user interfaces distract us from the simplicity

225
00:14:16,340 --> 00:14:19,600
 of what's going on inside of computers, because you think, well, where's the button?

226
00:14:19,600 --> 00:14:22,900
 And the answer is, oh, there's probably some command inside this computer that does what

227
00:14:22,900 --> 00:14:24,440
 the button does.

228
00:14:24,440 --> 00:14:32,680
 So I have a former student of mine who actually wrote the scene in, I think, maybe it was

229
00:14:32,680 --> 00:14:33,680
 Matrix 2.

